Similar to the popular "C" series Kahr pistols for CCW the "P" series is Kahr's premium CCW line. Only selling because I got a PM40, the lower capacity compact version of this pistol and I find I carry it more often.

This pistol has the original high polish blue finish, strawed small parts (straw color is very generous), and is fitted with original one piece checkered Bakelite (early plastic) excellent grips with no cracks or chips, with the “ČZ” logos molded on the top. The pistol is housed in an original leather flap CZ 27 holster displaying a big Nazi stamp (The Reichsadler of Nazi Germany) inside flap. The pistol is complete with an original factory magazine stamped on the bottom of the base “P. Mod. 27”. This is a rather common WW2 German-issued pistol in uncommonly nice condition. CZ 27 was one of the most widely-issued non-German pocket pistols of WW2. They are extremely well-made and overbuilt. While most CZ 27 variants are quite common, it is difficult to find early pistols like this one in such exceptional condition. This is the high polish variant, made to the highest quality. The finish on early CZ 27 pistols, with serial numbers ranging from 20,500 to 230,000, was bright blue. As the production progressed, the finish changed to dull blue, then to half blue and half phosphate, and finally to all phosphate. This pistol displays a Nazi-German Military “eagle/WaA 76” WaffenAmt acceptance mark (on right frame, top slide, and barrel). The barrel is stamped with an “eagle clutching a swastika” German Military test proof mark. The top of the slide is marked “BÖHMISCHE WAFFENFABRIK A.G. IN PRAG” (Česká zbrojovka [CZ] in Prague) followed by the Nazi proof and serial number. Left side of the slide is marked “Pistole Modell 27 Kal. 7,65”. All the numbered parts are matching (right on frame, top of slide, left on side plate, and on barrel). In March 1939, Germany occupied all of Czechoslovakia, and in early 1941, all CZ 27 pistol production was diverted to the German war effort. Czechoslovak sources put the beginning serial number of German Military production at 20,500 (the serial number of our early pistol is 141,755). Between 620,000 and 650,000 CZ 27 pistols were manufactured in total, 452,500 of those under German occupation.To buy or call >>>> CZ CZECH CZ 27 EARLY HIGH POLISH GERMAN ARMY ISSUE

title: For Sale:  CZECH CZ 27 EARLY HIGH POLISH GERMAN ARMY ISSUE (ICN8280)
postcontent: We have an early production, .32 ACP, 70% blue, beautiful CZ 27 (vz. 27) pistol. Serial Number: 70,101. This is the high polish variant, made to the highest quality. The finish on early CZ 27 pistols, with serial numbers ranging from 20,500 to 230,000, was bright blue. As the production progressed, the finish changed to dull blue, then to half blue and half phosphate, and finally to all phosphate. This pistol displays a Nazi-German Military “eagle/WaA 76” WaffenAmt acceptance mark (on right frame, top slide, and barrel). The barrel is stamped with an “eagle clutching a swastika” German Military test proof mark. The top of the slide is marked “BÖHMISCHE WAFFENFABRIK A.G. IN PRAG” (Česká zbrojovka [CZ] in Prague) followed by the Nazi proof and serial number. Left side of the slide is marked “Pistole Modell 27 Kal. 7,65”. All the numbered parts are matching (right on frame, top of slide, left on side plate, and on barrel). In March 1939, Germany occupied all of Czechoslovakia, and in early 1941, all CZ 27 pistol production was diverted to the German war effort. Czechoslovak sources put the beginning serial number of German Military production at 20,500 (the serial number of our early pistol is 70,101). Between 620,000 and 650,000 CZ 27 pistols were manufactured in total, 452,500 of those under German occupation. The pistol is complete with an original factory magazine stamped on the bottom of the base “P. Mod. 27”. This pistol has the original high polish blue finish, strawed small parts (straw color is very generous), and is fitted with original one piece checkered Bakelite (early plastic) excellent grips with no cracks or chips, with the “ČZ” logos molded on the top. This is a rather common WW2 German-issued pistol in uncommonly nice condition. CZ 27 was one of the most widely-issued non-German pocket pistols of WW2. They are extremely well-made and overbuilt. While most CZ 27 variants are quite common, it is difficult to find early pistols like this one in such exceptional condition. The pistol is housed in an original leather flap holster.To buy or call >>>> CZ CZECH CZ 27 EARLY HIGH POLISH GERMAN ARMY ISSUE

title: For Sale:  CZ CZECH CZ 27 EARLY HIGH POLISH GERMAN ARMY ISSUE (ICN8274)
postcontent: We have an early production, .32 ACP, 75% blue, beautiful, mint CZ 27 (vz. 27) Pistol. Serial Number: 59,799. This is the high polish variant, made to the highest quality. The finish on early CZ 27 pistols, with serial numbers ranging from 20,500 to 230,000, was bright blue. As the production progressed, the finish changed to dull blue, then to half blue and half phosphate, and finally to all phosphate. This pistol displays a Nazi-German Military “eagle/WaA 76” WaffenAmt acceptance mark (on right frame, top slide, and barrel). The barrel is stamped with an “eagle clutching a swastika” German Military test proof mark. The top of the slide is marked “BÖHMISCHE WAFFENFABRIK A.G. IN PRAG” (Česká zbrojovka [CZ] in Prague) followed by the Nazi proof and serial number. Left side of the slide is marked “Pistole Modell 27 Kal. 7,65”. All the numbered parts are matching (right on frame, top of slide, left on side plate, and on barrel). In March 1939, Germany occupied all of Czechoslovakia, and in early 1941, all CZ 27 pistol production was diverted to the German war effort. Czechoslovak sources put the beginning serial number of German Military production at 20,500 (the serial number of our early pistol is 59,799). Between 620,000 and 650,000 CZ 27 pistols were manufactured in total, 452,500 of those under German occupation. The pistol is complete with an original factory magazine stamped on the bottom of the base “P. Mod 27”. This pistol has the original high polish blue finish, strawed small parts (straw color is generous), and is fitted with original one piece checkered Bakelite (early plastic) excellent grips with no cracks or chips, with the “ČZ” logos molded on the top. This is a rather common WW2 German-issued pistol in uncommonly nice condition. CZ 27 was one of the most widely-issued non-German pocket pistols of WW2. They are extremely well-made and overbuilt. While most CZ 27 variants are quite common, it is difficult to find early pistols like this one in such exceptional condition. The pistol is housed in an original leather flap holster. The holster is stamped with an “eagle clutching a swastika” German Military test proof mark.To buy or call >>>> CZ CZECH CZ 27 EARLY HIGH POLISH GERMAN ARMY ISSUE

title: For Sale:  CZECH CZ 27 VERY RARE EARLY HIGH POLISH GERMAN ARMY ISSUE WITHOUT SERIAL NUMBER (ICN8282)
postcontent: We have an early production, very hard-to-find, .32 ACP, 75% blue, mint CZ 27 (vz. 27) “No Serial Number” pistol in good condition. This is one of the most beautiful early high polish CZ 27 pistols we have ever seen. Perfect mechanical condition, and an excellent like new bore. Serial Number: NONE. This CZ 27 pistol has no serial numbers! The frames do not display a Nazi-German Military “eagle/WaA 76” WaffenAmt acceptance mark. The barrel is stamped with an “eagle clutching a swastika” German Military test proof mark and a “WaA76” WaffenAmt acceptance mark. No marking anywhere else. There has been a lot of speculation about what these pistols were used for. According to some experts, this pistol was sanitized for clandestine use by SS or Gestapo. In any case, this pistol should be of extreme interest to the growing number of Czech pistol collectors. This pistol has the original high polish blue finish, strawed small parts (straw color is very generous), and is fitted with original one piece checkered Bakelite (early plastic) excellent grips with no cracks or chips, with the “ČZ” logos molded on the top. The pistol is housed in an original brown leather flap CZ 27 holster. The pistol is complete with an original factory magazine stamped on the bottom of the base “P. Mod. 27”. This is a rather common WW2 German-issued pistol in uncommonly nice condition. CZ 27 was one of the most widely-issued non-German pocket pistols of WW2. They are extremely well-made and overbuilt. While most CZ 27 variants are quite common, it is difficult to find early pistols like this one in such exceptional condition. This is the high polish variant, made to the highest quality. The finish on early CZ 27 pistols, with serial numbers ranging from 20,500 to 230,000, was bright blue. As the production progressed, the finish changed to dull blue, then to half blue and half phosphate, and finally to all phosphate. The top of the slide is marked “BÖHMISCHE WAFFENFABRIK A.G. IN PRAG” (Česká zbrojovka [CZ] in Prague). Left side of the slide is marked “Pistole Modell 27 Kal. 7,65”. In March 1939, Germany occupied all of Czechoslovakia, and in early 1941, all CZ 27 pistol production was diverted to the German war effort. Czechoslovak sources put the beginning serial number of German Military production at 20,500. Between 620,000 and 650,000 CZ 27 pistols were manufactured in total, 452,500 of those under German occupation.To buy or call >>>> CZ CZECH CZ 27 VERY RARE EARLY HIGH POLISH GERMAN ARMY ISSUE WITHOUT SERIAL NUMBER

title: For Sale/Trade:  Rare Collectible Early PT-92
postcontent: Here's a rare early model PT-92 that appears unfired. It is a 1983 vintage production, one of the first made and it still had the European magazine release on the bottom of the handgrip. Most PT-92 mags have both cuts so it's not really a big deal. I just prefer the newer type near the trigger and am willing to either sell this weapon or trade it for one of those PT-92s, hopefully a pre-decocker model but not a deal breaker. Alot of people think this is a clone...copy...etc..of the Beretta. These weapons were built on Beretta tooling when their contract for the Brazilian militar contract expired in Brazil but it is an improved version of the 92. The Taurus introduced the square trigger guard and kept the safety on the frame where it belongs. Also, you can carry this weapon cocked and locked like a 1911 and it has a forged guide rod as opposed to the Beretta plastic one. The gun is forged on frame, slide and barrel, signature Taurus features (Forjas Taurus/Taurus Forge). It comes in original box with warranty card and an awesome parts breakdown foldout poster. It is as nice as you will find an early one. It has upgrades including Hogue allen grip screws and Wolf hammer and guide rod springs. I will trade for a little newer PT-92 but don't want any abused or dropped weapons. Thanks for looking.
